    {
      "id": "1361084621978341550",
      "type": "Default",
      "timestamp": "2025-04-13T23:04:21.609+02:00",
      "timestampEdited": "2025-04-14T10:09:03.791+02:00",
      "callEndedTimestamp": null,
      "isPinned": false,
      "content": "- Importance of Practicing\n  - *Practice makes perfect.*\n  -  You have been told this so many times but many people fail to listen when it comes to aim. It's such a simple tip yet very hard to follow. \n  - Many people fail to keep dedications when they fail to see massive improvement. \n  - Making a set routine and practicing routines that help with your aiming weaknesses, you will see the most improvements. \n\n- Patience\n  - Nobody likes practicing aim but when you think about the improvement to come, you should remember what you want. \n  - Everyone wants good aim and it doesn't happen overnight. Trust in the process of aim training. It will work as long as you are dedicated. \n  - You will gain a slim margin every day with dedication and consistency.\n\n- Controller aim training allows you to control better how you look and how your thumb should respond to aim assist toggling (on/off).\n  - It allows you to learn to loosen your thumb's movement on the right stick when it activates, and tensing the movement when the aim assist deactivates.\n  -  So you are \"trying to aim less accurately with your thumb in a way\" when it toggles on, and you \"start aiming well with your thumb\" when it turns off.\n\n- Lining your shots up and using movement to help you aim your shots can help land more consistent shots and is good to practice.\n\n- Aim actively, remember when you are aiming hardcore in aim training against the dummies? Aim like that, and you will aim on focus and not passively or autopiloted aim.\n\n- Watch from [here](https://youtu.be/fu36ALOG5DQ?t=10) for controller explanation, Aim Assist, Modifications to controller, optimizing strafing and looking using the joysticks, etc",
